description:
On this episode of The Zach Show, Annette Nenner and Christian Hardinghaus discuss the disappearance of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon on the infamous Pianista Trail in Panama, the case analysis and elements of the disappearance that don't match up, the photos recovered from the SD card, accident versus crime theories, whether this case was covered up by Panamanian authorities, and more. 
 
GUEST BIO: Christian Hardinghaus is a New York Times bestselling author, investigative journalist, and media scientist who analyzed thousands of files related to the case of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon. Annette Nenner is a journalist, writer, editor, and traveler who spent over five months in the Boquete region of Panama interviewing dozens of witnesses related to the case of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon and conducted intensive on-site research, exploring the Panamanian cloud forest day and night tracing the paths that the girls could have taken. Hardinghaus and Nenner are co-authors of the book Still Lost In Panama: The Real Tragedy On Pianista Trail.

comments.text: I feel kind of silly saying this but what happened to Lisanne and Kris gives me this deep sense of sadness and grief few other things outside of personal traumatic experiences ever have. Every few years I will be dragged back into this rabbit-hole with seemingly no answer, watching hours upon hours of videos relating to the case. A part of me just wants to know what exactly happened so badly, but it's not out of morbid curiosity. At this point I feel connected to them and I just wish they could finally truly be put to rest. Every time I get back into this case a sadness just keeps building and building and it's like there is no way to let it out. It's like there are all these emotions of sadness and frustration, confusion and fear and no way to make it all feel real and just process it. I just have this sickening feeling hyper-focused on how their lives didn't matter, my life doesn't matter and my feelings of intense sadness don't matter either and won't change anything. I wish so much for that not to be the case. This whole case is literally such a living nightmare, deep down to the core, but what bothers me most is the disrespect and speculation that has twisted their tragedy into a spectacle. I guess, what would really bring me peace is if that whole spectacle came to an end and at some point we finally knew what truly happened to them so they can rest in peace.
comments.author: @monamonarchist7611

comments.text: I read the book, and it honestly seemed extremely thorough. There is on piece of information from this case that I cannot shake. The report on April 4th by German tourist who reported to the ranger of the blood curdling screams from a female, and the men he saw pursuing these screams.  The very scream that scared the living shit out of this man that motivated him to run the hell out of the area.  This was reported on the Los Quetzales sendero which is extremely close to the pipeline trail, the other trail that i believe the 2 young ladies where heard to be discussing along with the Pianista or also researched on the schools computer.  I am assuming this man new about this case by April 4th or no? To me that could be very telling if he did not know about this case as there would be no subconscious influences motivating him to be trying to find in his mind something wrong in the area. Also was he out on the trail purely for vacation purposes or was he also partially there as part of a unofficial volunteer in this tragic case.  This is one of the numerous coincidences that I cannot accept ( if legitimate ) that leads me to believe that this is almost comically NOT  plausible that these girls were    only just lost..  If any of you guys could shed any more light on this portion of the case it would be greatly appreciated.  Everything about this case screams everything that is foul and wrong with this world and I pray to God the truth will be revealed one day, even if it means that the were really JUST lost, which unfortunately I believe in every fiber of my being that is extremely unlikely.
comments.author: @DanielSzabo-l7z

comments.text: I was born on the same exact day as Lisanne Froon; September 24, 1991. It really makes me think, we went thru so many of the same world events and social/cultural phenomenon together. Any memory I have, whether it's the release of Ocarina of Time on the N64 or the original Pokemon cards; good chance she would have had her own strong memories of it as well. We probably had the same memories of 9/11... sitting in class; maybe your teacher also watched with your class live as the planes hit the towers, broadcast on one of those CRT's on those portable stands they would keep them on. We would both have much clearer memories of every September 24 up until 2013; while for the vast majority of people it either held no significance or they weren't even born yet. I believe I have a very similar personality type to her as well; shy, sensitive, but craving for adventure, always pushing for personal growth and chasing after experiences as well as just having a deep-seeded need for love and connection on a human level. We were also both similar heights; I'm 188 and a half but she was 184; damn, that's tall for a woman! We also apparently graduated Uni the same year and with the same major. The year was 2014; her degree was more specific, I just got a major in Psychology. Thanks to that I know exactly what I was doing in March, April of 2014. Our Spring semester that year ended on April 4th, we had a 'reading-week' until the 8th and started final Exams on the 9th. So while Lisanne was taking those night photos, one of her last days on this earth, I know exactly where I was; I was at home, staying up all night as well cramming for my final I had put off until the last minute. By the time I was picking up my diploma she was already gone. Somehow, it makes me happy to have that very specific memory of where I was when this happened to her. It makes me feel a lot closer to her as a result. In the end, a bit upwards of 300,000 people were probably born on September, 24, 1991. I don't know how many are still alive, but Lisanne, you will always be in my memory and I'll make it to the finish line for the both of us.
comments.author: @bananakatana123

comments.text: I've been secretly grieving the death of these two girls for years now; reading all the reports and watching all the new videos every few years or so. Most of them are ridiculous and disrespectful to their memory; with the exaggerated titles and idiotic thumbnails like this one. I don't really care though, it stopped bothering me a long time ago. Every time I come back I dig deeper and deeper and get lost in their story for days. I uncover tiny little details that are so human it feels like I knew them personally. The truth is, they were wonderful human beings, both of them. I know everyone says that about the dead even when it's not true, but in this case it is. I feel that soon a huge breakthrough will be made in this case, and we will be able to finally prove a lot of the details of their disappearance and death. A team of wonderful fellows are working on it; very respectful, passionate and meticulously intelligent and rational-minded. What they found reveals even more heartbreaking details about just how kind hearted these girls were. For a long time it felt like there was nothing anyone could do anymore; they've been gone for over 11 years now. I feel like once we finally fully uncover the story of what happened those days in the jungle it will finally give the families true peace and will forever honor their memories.

comments.text:
A friend of mine went missing on a hike in a different country in 2018. The search there was so poorly organised that our country flew helicopters, mountain rescuers and dog teams there to search themselves. It does not surprise me that a country like Panama didn't have the resources and organised search that us westerners would expect or wish for. 
I think the most likely event is that these two young women had a hiking accident and succumbed to injuries or the elements. I do not think foul play was involved. However, from personal experience I can only say that as loved ones, you'll never really have closure. You'll always think about the possibilities, the likely and the unlikely ones. My friend went on his vacation to hike a difficult mountain. He's presumed to have died on it and the search is long abandoned. It's likely that he did die on that mountain. But we don't know. None of his things were ever found. Do you go on a mountain expedition with all your things that you brought for travel? The mountain has a base camp and another camp, and he was not seen in either of them. Nobody saw him even though there were multiple groups on the mountain. You see what I mean? There is a likely story of events but there is no certainty. And because of that, there is no closure. I can only imagine the families of these two young women feel very similar.

comments.text:
I have been following the case since the begining.

I have over 30 years of experience - 3 of them at night - working in tropical forests like the one where the girls disappeared. The theory that best fits all the available data - in my opinion - is that the girls got lost after something strange happened on the trail.

It could have been someone or something that scared them, or they simply decided to relieve themselves off the trail and were unable to return. I have worked with many people in the forest and this is a common practice.

If foul play occurred, it was before they left the trail or after with the backpack. I do not believe in cannibals, organ trafficking and photos altered by bandits.

I do not believe that they were kidnapped for several days either. The data from their phones and especially from the night photos do not suggest this. However, what happened to the backpack is what makes me not 100% sure that they simply got lost.

That said, I must point out that tropical forests are extremely dangerous, even for experienced hikers.

If you doubt try by yourself. I do not agree with several statements that the girls were literally walking in the backyards of houses on a trail where it is impossible to get lost.

It is always possible to get lost.

The forest they were in seems very dense and vast to me from the videos of Romain C that I watched. I have gotten lost countless times on easier trails than this one in Panama. Trails that I know well.

This happens mainly on the way back. Because the light conditions change - fog - and there are small paths - forks - that are only visible on the way back... Now imagine two girls who did this long trail for the first time, without GPS, without knowing the place and without much water or clothes.

It would be almost impossible for them not to get disoriented at some point. And the photos before the Mirador suggest that they had doubts about the path even on the way up. On these trails there are people and animals that can create false paths anywhere at any time.

Trees can fall, causing you to leave the trail to go around. Anyway.

Another thing is the holes in the forest floor. In Brazil, there is a famous case of Kamal Guster who disappeared COMPLETLY AND FOREVER when he was only 80 meters away from his friend in the forest. I have fallen into a hole in the forest once. If you hit your head and the hole is small but deep you may never be found. Rivers are also very dangerous. Anyway.

Nature is a formidable killer. When you are at the top of the mountain, the simple decision to take the wrong path down in a moment of distraction or due to dehydration can be fatal. It is curious how few people here have realized that the path beyond Mirador is a mirror in terms of reference points in relation to the path up.

The reference points are repeated, giving the impression that you may be descending on the correct side of the mountain. But you are not. Anyway, I have been through countless things and met many strange people on trails too, so it may also be possible that they initially suffered foul play and then got lost. Best regards.

comments.text:
Lots of falsehoods here although not because of the creator.
The backpack was not dry or clean when it was found this is 100% false. When you stop to think about it for a second even not knowing the truth about it you realize this isn't possible. Anyone going hiking going to know staying clean is not a option and everything gets dirty. Hell it can be seen in the pictures and clean not what it is.
The bra being neatly folded...ask any woman what they do with their unwire bra in very hot, humid, wet  environment and you get you answer.
The shorts were not found neatly folded on a rock but infact found in the river.
The ankle that was found had three breaks and the pelvis has another showing one had been injured.
The skin showed an infection you get from long term walking in a hot humid environment.
The pictures started the same night a group was out searching for them making noise and using light to try and get their attention.
The supposed missing picture was one that likely never existed given this was a known bug with digital cameras of this type.
Bone being bleached is also very easy to explain given they were five miles away from a volcano and the chemicals required to  do this to bones would have been in the soil all over the place.
The bones where not infact unmarked but showed signs of animals. What was stated in the report the bones showed no signs of dismemberment which were the confusion likely comes from. 

What likely happened is they got lost and wandered around for sometime before one got injured.
The checking use of the phones makes sense and the lack of sim being inputted later also does. Running out of power and conserving it, times goes by and you are starving and dehydrated you look for signal and then give up doing anything else when there none.
As for more bones not being found its a jungle with animals and a river that has the nickname meat grind.
Most of what got washed into the river likely got pulverised and is now too small to be found

Does this 100% rule out a crime not but it points very strongly in the direction of two people getting lost and a sad ending.
The problem here is a lot of mis information got put online that was infact totally false. Once you see the actually facts it becomes far less likely that a crime happened and a tragedy did.

Too many falsehoods got out there and not enough critical thinking was done by online sleuths.

comments.text:
Rarely have I seen such sloppy work. And this guy calls himself a scientist...

1) Absence of evidence isn't evidence of absence. This argument is used a lot, but most notably when it comes to seeing the girls. Logic 101.

2) "the bones show no damage", but in the next senctence they're 'destroyed' and 'bleached', this clearly is damage. The jungle has a huge amount of different sub-environments, some of them easily could be alkaline which can speed up bleaching. Also, there are other animals than predators in the forest that will eat human tissue...

3) You can't say anything about the photo's since you don't have the originals. We have to take them at face value until they conflict with other HARD evidence. Not flimsy witness statements (the weakest evidence there is)

4) The Pianista Puzzle has shown  to the verge of certainty that the girls made the picture. They used a 3d reconstruction. Look it up. These 2 goofballs are just speculation without ANY evidence.

5) "I don't build my own idea", yes, yes you clearly do. You think things are not likely, therefore you don't believe them.

6) After 8 days in the jungle you can't say anything about the mental state of the girls. If you don't think the photo's are logical, that's exactly what you expect. 

7) on picture 509. The picture was called 'deleted' by the NFI because  there was a picture 508 and 510 and there was root data on 509. It seemed deleted. However, it could very well be that the picture was never made but this was a malfunction. It could very well be moment of the accident: falling and water disconnecting the battery. This would also explain why the camera was off for 8 days;  it got wet and they didn't want to turn it on.

8) phone calls. Again, their argument is: " I can't imagine". This is not evidence. You don't know the mental state nor were they were. 
Also: it's not about what experts think.... It' s about what the girls thought at that moment. 

9) "what you expect". My god.... really? 

10) thumbs up? Really? Is this your 'evidence'? You are claiming the involvement of someone based on one of the most universal hand gestures in the world. 
You don't want to cast suspicion yet that exactly what you do.

11) You can't IMAGINE lost or accident can't be without foul play aka tunnel vision.

Edit: removed some spelling errors. Typing on a phone is harder than one might expect :)
